node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin We need to be talking about the challenges that exist for folks in larger bodies who are recovering from eating disorders. For ex, I follow someone in recovery in a larger body on TikTok who gets hate comment after hate comment, simply for existing in her body.'.

node.text:
As clinicians we need to both acknowledge our privilege (if we live in smaller bodies) and validate that for those recovering in a larger body they face systemic fat phobia.
.
I’ve had clients in larger bodies recover AND we have to talk about the barriers that exist and make things difficult-such as poor medical care that may encourage the ED, bullying online, spaces and clothing that are not accessible to their bodies.
.
If you’re recovering in a larger body-YOUR BODY IS NOT WRONG. Society is.
.
Myself and my amazing team are HAES and fat positive therapists (ie we don’t believe folks in larger bodies should just be accepted-they deserve to be celebrated). 💃🏼
.

node.text:
SAY IT LOUDER FOR THE PEOPLE IN THE BACK! 🎤⠀⠀
.
You can’t tell if someone has an eating disorder by looking at them, and specific diagnoses don’t have a “look.”⠀
.
Eating disorders are mental illnesses that sometimes have physical symptoms and effects – someone's weight or appearance doesn't define their struggle.⠀
.
You can have an eating disorder at ANY weight.
.

node.text:
It might be impossible. It might take 20
Or 30 years. And I’ve decided that regardless, I want to do everything in my power to help organize advocacy efforts to get the diagnostic criteria for anorexia changed to remove the ‘low weight’ component.
.
BED and bulimia do not have a weight criteria in the DSM. Those of us in the field know that you can’t determine how severely someone is struggling on the basis of their weight.
.
This leads to folks in larger bodies not receiving adequate diagnosis and treatment. It leads to people’s eating disorders not always being taken seriously on the basis of their weight-and this is NOT ok.
.
I’m sure some people will think I’m wasting my time or this change can’t be made-but I’d rather at least try and give it my all.
.
I have a meeting on Monday with two researchers (because the DSM folks care a lot about the research) and talked with Chevese Turner yesterday who was instrumental in getting BED added to the DSM. 👊🏻
.
I share all of this because I want to use my platform to help enact change. Anyone with DSM committee connections feel free to reach out lol.
.

May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin For For some, part of their eating disorder may be a trauma response. In a world and a body that feel unsafe, they try to find a sense of safety through ED behaviors. ED behaviors may provide a feeling of 'safety' in the short term, but in the long-term they are life-destroying.'.

node.text:
In the past, I didn’t want to feel the impact of trauma-and so I stuffed it down. 
.
I thought that I was ‘fine’ until I clearly wasn’t.
.
My attempts at numbing out and ‘finding safety’ through ED behaviors took over my life and made me miserable, depressed, and a shell of my former self.
.
It turned out I needed therapy and safe relationships to truly heal. 
.
Avoiding my feelings only made them stronger-and made me dependent on all of these behaviors to try to numb out. 
.

node.text:
The best weight range for you is the one that enables you to live your most authentic and joyful life.
.
@paigepayne_creations did the art for this and is also just a wonderful human. Appreciate her 💕
.
If you have to restrict food, obsessively exercise, or purge to maintain a certain weight-that’s not the right weight for you. I know this can be hard to sit with, especially for those who face weight stigma due to their size AND you deserve so much more than a life spent suppressing your natural weight, and ultimately suppressing your life experiences.
.
We all only get one life-and I want you to eventually be able to experience it more fully. 💕
.
**and we have to acknowledge how weight stigma and oppression towards marginalized folks can impact their life experiences. 
.

May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin Harvard did an 100 year study and found that the people who lived the longest, were those with the most connected relationships. So going to grab ice cream with a friend is generally healthier than eating a plate of carrots alone.'.

node.text:
Plus a plate of carrots may be filling but not very satisfying and also won’t have long ‘staying power’ in terms of hunger due to the lack of fat etc. So if you’re craving veggies far better to pair them with ranch, hummus, butter, etc. (as this also helps with the absorption of fat-soluble nutrients). 
.
Anyway, point being that social connections were found in an 100 year study by Harvard to be the biggest predictor of health and longevity. 
.
If you don’t have a ton of friends, don’t use this to beat yourself up! Just use it as recovery motivation as EDs can really isolate you.
.
